1
00:00:00,976 --> 00:00:28,570
Namo dasa bhagavato hara-hato sama-sambuddhasa Namo dasa bhagavato hara-hato sama-sambuddhasa Namo dasa bhagavato hara-hato sama-sambuddhasa

2
00:00:31,164 --> 00:00:37,079
the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:37,220 --> 00:00:43,115
So we're using this book, In the Buddha's Words by Vikubodhi to investigate the discourses.

4
00:00:44,277 --> 00:00:48,723
And we've moved into the chapter concerning the Buddha himself.

5
00:00:48,863 --> 00:01:10,656
And last week we sort of discussed how people see the Buddha, either as a sort of humanist who came up with a wonderful ethical code to make us all happy, right over, right as far as a supra-human being who's capable of enormous and amazing things.

6
00:01:11,902 --> 00:01:15,284
So there's a huge, vast way that we can interpret the Buddha.

7
00:01:16,986 --> 00:01:23,393
Here, of course, in the West, we tend to see him much more as a human being who discovered a path.

8
00:01:24,072 --> 00:01:33,421
And some of us believe that this Nirvana that he talks about, you can get it, but you've only got one life, so you've got to be pretty lucky.

9
00:01:34,944 --> 00:01:39,427
And others think that, well, you go on, and so in future lives you'll be able to get it.

10
00:01:40,748 --> 00:01:41,790
So...

11
00:01:43,052 --> 00:01:51,823
This particular discourse that has been chosen gives us these two sides and we'll see how the mythic side of the Buddha was built up.

12
00:01:52,564 --> 00:02:00,415
It concentrates on the conception and birth of his life.

13
00:02:02,138 --> 00:02:07,525
So I'll sort of read it and then make comments as I go along.

14
00:02:08,094 --> 00:02:13,699
Remember that this is an oral tradition and therefore it has a sort of repetitious feel about it.

15
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:15,602
So I won't actually put you through that misery.

16
00:02:17,783 --> 00:02:19,306
I'll just read out the kernel bits.

17
00:02:21,288 --> 00:02:22,307
Thus have I heard.

18
00:02:22,328 --> 00:02:33,498
So remember it's Ananda who remembers all that the Buddha said and at the first meeting after his death, he's the one who related the words of the Buddha.

19
00:02:33,919 --> 00:02:37,663
So it always begins with, all these discourses begin with thus have I heard.

20
00:02:38,824 --> 00:02:45,512
On one occasion, the Blessed One was living at Sarvati in Jeta's Grove and Atipindika's Path.

21
00:02:45,532 --> 00:02:49,915
Now, Atipindika was one of these new breed of people who was a merchant.

22
00:02:49,936 --> 00:02:57,743
This was something quite new, say, within the last, say, hundred or so hundred years of the Buddha's, around the Buddha's time.

23
00:02:58,145 --> 00:03:03,330
And it all, it's all part and parcel of a change in that society towards...

24
00:03:04,525 --> 00:03:12,495
ruled by a group of elites, which was what we would call a sort of democracy, to kingship.

25
00:03:13,515 --> 00:03:18,241
And Anathapindika was a very successful businessman, a merchant.

26
00:03:19,402 --> 00:03:23,227
So in those days they were moving away from barter to using money.

27
00:03:24,288 --> 00:03:25,469
That was the shift.

28
00:03:26,057 --> 00:03:32,387
And Anathapindika, upon hearing of the Buddha even, pimples was all over his skin.

29
00:03:32,467 --> 00:03:35,932
And when he finally met him, he determined that this was the man.

30
00:03:36,713 --> 00:03:41,961
And he determined to buy him a piece of land for his monastics.

31
00:03:41,980 --> 00:03:49,391
So by this time, the Buddha had gathered around him some monks and some women, some nuns.

32
00:03:50,052 --> 00:03:51,254
And he bought...

33
00:03:51,538 --> 00:03:53,983
this field from Prince Jeta.

34
00:03:54,824 --> 00:03:56,545
And Jeta didn't want to sell it.

35
00:03:57,086 --> 00:03:59,411
So he said, well, what would you sell it for?

36
00:03:59,871 --> 00:04:02,955
He said, not even if you covered the whole ground with gold coins.

37
00:04:03,417 --> 00:04:06,741
So Anathapindika went on to cover the whole ground with gold coins.

38
00:04:07,323 --> 00:04:10,807
And in this way, it became the Buddha's first monastery.

39
00:04:11,408 --> 00:04:12,590
And it was at Savati.

40
00:04:12,669 --> 00:04:17,057
Savati was the capital of Kosala, which was north of the Ganges.

41
00:04:17,358 --> 00:04:19,480
And Pasenadi was a great supporter.

42
00:04:19,500 --> 00:04:23,463
The King Pasenadi was a great supporter of the Buddha.

43
00:04:23,483 --> 00:04:27,488
Same caste, the Borya caste.

44
00:04:27,509 --> 00:04:30,752
Okay, so they're in this grove, they're in this monastery.

45
00:04:31,012 --> 00:04:37,098
Now a number of monks were sitting in the assembly hall when they had met together on returning from arms round.

46
00:04:38,220 --> 00:04:41,543
And after their meal, this discussion arose amongst them.

47
00:04:41,923 --> 00:04:46,048
It is wonderful, friends, it is marvellous how mighty and powerful is the Tathagata.

48
00:04:46,535 --> 00:04:57,468
For he is able to know about the Buddhas of the past who attained final Nibbana, cut the tangle of proliferation, broke the cycle, ended the round and surmounted all suffering.

49
00:04:58,348 --> 00:05:12,605
That for those blessed ones, their birth was thus, their names was thus, their clans was thus, their moral discipline was thus, their qualities of concentration were thus, their wisdom was thus, their meditative dwellings were thus, their liberation was thus.

50
00:05:13,206 --> 00:05:14,127
So here...

51
00:05:14,345 --> 00:05:20,271
they're saying it's an amazing thing that the Buddha also knows all about the past of Buddhas.

52
00:05:21,012 --> 00:05:26,137
Now remember, the East and the ancient world always thought in cyclic time.

53
00:05:26,577 --> 00:05:29,000
You know, they didn't think in linear time.

54
00:05:29,019 --> 00:05:42,394
And so you always get this, with all these saints at the time, like the Nigantha, who was the head of the Jain sect, there are always the Jinas, the victorious ones,

55
00:05:42,644 --> 00:05:44,726
They always look back to a whole train of them.

56
00:05:45,608 --> 00:05:51,574
If you actually know, I don't know whether you know a modern Hindu saint called Nisigarh the Maharaj.

57
00:05:51,975 --> 00:05:58,202
He wrote, I am that.

58
00:05:58,483 --> 00:05:58,963
Yeah, that's it.

59
00:06:00,084 --> 00:06:06,372
He also says that he's part of a row of equally enlightened persons.

60
00:06:07,483 --> 00:06:13,692
So the Buddha's obviously been talking about these past Buddhas and they were quite amazed that he knew so much about them.

61
00:06:15,975 --> 00:06:22,004
Now when this was said, the Venerable Ananda said to the monks, friends, Tathagatas are wonderful and have wonderful qualities.

62
00:06:22,084 --> 00:06:24,747
Tathagatas are marvellous and have marvellous qualities.

63
00:06:25,168 --> 00:06:28,353
Remember the word Tathagata is what the Buddha referred to himself as.

64
00:06:28,874 --> 00:06:35,262
And it means one who has gone there, one who has arrived, best translated as the transcendent.

65
00:06:37,336 --> 00:06:45,403
However, their discussion was interrupted for the Blessed One rose from meditation when it was evening, went to the assembly hall and sat down on a seat made ready.

66
00:06:45,723 --> 00:06:46,783
And then he addressed the monks.

67
00:06:47,764 --> 00:06:50,146
For what discussion are you sitting together here?

68
00:06:52,028 --> 00:06:58,254
Here, Venerable Sir, we were sitting in the assembly hall when we met together and then they go through the whole business that I've just told you.

69
00:06:58,935 --> 00:07:01,817
They came back from harm's round and said how wonderful he was.

70
00:07:03,660 --> 00:07:05,300
And the Blessed One said...

71
00:07:05,939 --> 00:07:11,716
That being so, Ananda explained more fully the Tathagata's wonderful and marvellous qualities.

72
00:07:11,997 --> 00:07:17,855
So now Ananda really settles down to explain the wonderful things that happened around the Buddha's birth.

73
00:07:19,978 --> 00:07:25,004
That mindful and clearly comprehending, the Bodhisattva appeared in the Tusita heaven.

74
00:07:25,605 --> 00:07:33,276
So now the Bodhisattva is the name we give somebody who has determined to become a fully liberated being.

75
00:07:33,976 --> 00:07:35,678
Self-liberated being, right?

76
00:07:35,699 --> 00:07:36,439
The Bodhisattva.

77
00:07:36,961 --> 00:07:40,826
This translates into Mahayana, some of you know, as the Bodhicitta, right?

78
00:07:40,846 --> 00:07:42,627
The mind-seeking, enlightening.

79
00:07:43,528 --> 00:07:44,990
So...

80
00:07:46,067 --> 00:07:56,810
The Bodhisatta, actually some of you might know about Ajahn Mun, who was a modern, he died in the early 19th century.

81
00:07:57,392 --> 00:08:05,410
But he's very famous and from him there came a group of monks who were all also recognised to be fully liberated.

82
00:08:05,625 --> 00:08:23,769
And Ajahn Mung, whose biography is written by one of his disciples, Ajahn Mahabua, came to a point where he realised that in his past life he had made this determination to become a fully self-enlightened Buddha, decided it was too hard, gave it up and just became an Arahant.

83
00:08:27,057 --> 00:08:30,600
And they say that in Sri Lanka now there are five Bodhisattvas.

84
00:08:30,961 --> 00:08:37,167
There are five monks who've declared themselves as seeking fully self-liberated beings.

85
00:08:37,626 --> 00:08:40,409
This means that they start a dispensation like the Buddha did.

86
00:08:40,850 --> 00:08:43,393
They start a line of teaching.

87
00:08:45,674 --> 00:08:47,136
And he's in the Tusita heaven.

88
00:08:48,398 --> 00:08:49,980
There are six realms.

89
00:08:50,240 --> 00:08:51,100
See if I can remember them.

90
00:08:51,541 --> 00:08:52,542
The hell realms.

91
00:08:52,976 --> 00:09:05,907
The animal realms, the realms of the hungry ghosts, the human realm, the realm of the angry gods, and the deva realm, the realm of the happy gods.

92
00:09:06,697 --> 00:09:14,610
All these can be, if you're not into this sort of stuff, all these can be translated as human mental states.

93
00:09:14,630 --> 00:09:20,441
So when you're palatic and find yourself in a gutter, you're definitely in the animal realm.

94
00:09:20,782 --> 00:09:25,971
And if you were to really be born in that state, there wouldn't be much hope in Buddhist understanding.

95
00:09:26,726 --> 00:09:53,190
the hell realms would be equivalent to our ideas of psychosis and deep depressions and stuff like that there are places where you don't see an escape remember Dante wrote over the gates of hell abandon all hope ye who enter here that is hell the difference between hell and purgatory is that it's just as painful but purgatory offers a way out

96
00:09:55,110 --> 00:09:59,479
So there's no permanent hell in Buddhist understanding.

97
00:09:59,639 --> 00:10:01,101
Everything is impermanent.

98
00:10:01,744 --> 00:10:03,166
It just lasts a very long time.

99
00:10:05,350 --> 00:10:10,880
And then the hungry goat realm, that's the place where we suffer our griefs.

100
00:10:12,644 --> 00:10:13,947
The human realm we know.

101
00:10:14,315 --> 00:10:20,546
The angry gods are really the place where you have these battles between good and evil.

102
00:10:21,287 --> 00:10:25,134
And then finally, of course, the happy realm where all the millionaires live.

103
00:10:26,375 --> 00:10:29,421
Is that true?

104
00:10:30,734 --> 00:10:36,360
So now the next one is mindful and clearly comprehending the Bodhisattva remained in the Tushita heaven.

105
00:10:36,559 --> 00:10:42,745
It's understood that that's the last rebirth before he takes his final birth as a human being.

106
00:10:43,366 --> 00:10:45,509
So this Tushita heaven is a very happy place.

107
00:10:46,929 --> 00:10:51,153
For the whole of his lifespan the Bodhisattva remained in that Tushita heaven.

108
00:10:53,235 --> 00:10:55,158
Mindful and clearly comprehending.

109
00:10:55,999 --> 00:10:59,863
He's fully aware as we are presumably now.

110
00:11:00,974 --> 00:11:05,921
The Bodhisattva passed away from the Tushita heaven and descended into his mother's womb.

111
00:11:07,644 --> 00:11:13,793
And when the, oh yes, and now we get this wonderful passage which is really quite cinematic really.

112
00:11:14,573 --> 00:11:28,956
When the Bodhisattva passed away from the Tushita heaven and descended into his mother's womb, an immeasurable great radiance surpassing the divine majesty of the Devas appeared in the world with his Devas, Mara and Brahma.

113
00:11:29,307 --> 00:11:33,831
in this population with its ascetics and Brahmins, with its Devas and human beings.

114
00:11:34,572 --> 00:11:54,390
And even in those abysmal world intervals of vacancy, gloom and utter darkness, where the moon and sun, mighty and powerful as they are, cannot make their light prevail, there too an immeasurable great radiance surpassing the divine majesty of Devas appeared, and the beings reborn there perceived each other by that light.

115
00:11:54,991 --> 00:11:58,014
Ah, so indeed there are also other beings born here.

116
00:11:58,720 --> 00:12:08,671
And this 10,000 world system shook, quaked and trembled and again an immeasurable great radiance surpassing the divine majesty of the Devas appeared in the world.

117
00:12:09,692 --> 00:12:11,413
So that's a lovely vision, eh?

118
00:12:12,355 --> 00:12:13,596
Whether it's true or not is immaterial.

119
00:12:15,337 --> 00:12:27,731
When the Bodhisattva descended into his mother's womb, four young Devas came to guard him at the four quarters so that no humans or non-humans or anyone at all could harm the Bodhisattva or his mother.

120
00:12:30,158 --> 00:12:48,562
When the Bodhisattva descended into his mother's womb, she became intrinsically virtuous, refraining from killing living beings, from taking what is not given, from sexual misconduct, from false speech and from wise liquors and intoxicants, the basis of negligence.

121
00:12:48,581 --> 00:12:50,504
It's interesting, isn't it?

122
00:12:51,085 --> 00:12:56,672
A lot of the Christian mythology you see mirrored in these sorts of stories from the East.

123
00:12:58,187 --> 00:13:04,957
Other women give birth after carrying the child in a womb for nine or ten months, but not so the Bodhisattva's mother.

124
00:13:05,538 --> 00:13:13,149
The Bodhisattva's mother gave birth to him after carrying him in a womb for exactly ten months.

125
00:13:13,168 --> 00:13:20,099
Other women... Other women give birth seated or lying down, but not so the Bodhisattva's mother.

126
00:13:20,379 --> 00:13:23,124
The Bodhisattva's mother gave birth to him standing up.

127
00:13:24,004 --> 00:13:24,785
Now...

128
00:13:25,136 --> 00:13:34,446
I was thinking about that, and I presume it's to do with dignity, rather than flat on your back with your legs up in the air.

129
00:13:35,005 --> 00:13:38,529
You're standing in a very gentle pose.

130
00:13:39,330 --> 00:13:46,876
And I remember seeing a clip of a film of a woman in New Guinea, actually, hanging from a branch giving birth.

131
00:13:47,378 --> 00:13:48,599
So it's not unknown.

132
00:13:50,701 --> 00:13:51,701
That's so disappointing.

133
00:13:53,908 --> 00:13:55,149
And by herself, by the way.

134
00:13:57,032 --> 00:14:03,618
When the Bodhisattva came forth from his mother's womb, first Devas received him and then human beings.

135
00:14:03,778 --> 00:14:10,583
After all these phrases, he's always said, this too I remember as a wonderful and marvellous quality of the Blessed One.

136
00:14:10,604 --> 00:14:15,248
Now when the Bodhisattva came from his mother's womb, he did not touch the earth.

137
00:14:15,769 --> 00:14:23,054
The four young Devas received him and set him before his mother saying, Rejoice, O Queen, a son of great power has been born to you.

138
00:14:23,929 --> 00:14:27,374
That sounds biblical, doesn't it?

139
00:14:27,394 --> 00:14:36,586
When the Bodhisattva came forth from his mother's womb, he came forth unsullied, unsmeared by water, humus, blood, or any kind of impurity, clean or unsullied.

140
00:14:36,807 --> 00:14:39,169
Clean and unsullied.

141
00:14:39,190 --> 00:14:45,096
Suppose there were a gem placed on a fine cloth, then the gem would not smear the cloth, nor the cloth the gem.

142
00:14:45,597 --> 00:14:46,278
Why is that?

143
00:14:46,399 --> 00:14:48,402
Because of the purity of both.

144
00:14:48,881 --> 00:14:53,227
So too, when the Bodhisattva came forth, he came forth clean and unsullied.

145
00:14:54,962 --> 00:15:04,576
When the Bodhisattva came forth from his mother's womb, two jets of water appeared to pour from the sky, one cool and one warm, for bathing the Bodhisattva and his mother.

146
00:15:06,139 --> 00:15:19,418
And as soon as the Bodhisattva was born, he stood firmly on his feet on the ground, and then he took seven steps facing north, and with a white parasol held over him, he surveyed each quarter and uttered the words of the leader of the herd.

147
00:15:19,903 --> 00:15:21,586
I am the highest in the world.

148
00:15:22,047 --> 00:15:23,208
I am the best in the world.

149
00:15:23,489 --> 00:15:24,931
I am the foremost in the world.

150
00:15:25,351 --> 00:15:26,793
This is my last birth.

151
00:15:27,114 --> 00:15:29,677
There is no more renewed becoming for me.

152
00:15:30,298 --> 00:15:32,761
That's an image, isn't it?

153
00:15:33,423 --> 00:15:35,225
That little baby.

154
00:15:37,227 --> 00:15:38,990
That little crunched up creature.

155
00:15:39,051 --> 00:15:44,899
It's a great image, isn't it?

156
00:15:45,654 --> 00:15:55,850
When the Bodhisattva came forth from his brother's womb and in... Again, we have that repeat of the immeasurable great radiance surpassing the divine majesty of the Devas appeared in the world.

157
00:15:57,995 --> 00:16:07,690
And the 10,000 world system shook, quaked and trembled and there too an immeasurable great radiance surpassing the divine majesty of the Devas appeared in the world.

158
00:16:08,051 --> 00:16:11,296
So now, we have all this mythic stuff around the Buddha.

159
00:16:11,876 --> 00:16:12,658
And so...

160
00:16:13,533 --> 00:16:16,657
The Buddha now, as it were, brings us back to ground.

161
00:16:17,158 --> 00:16:17,918
And this is what he says.

162
00:16:17,938 --> 00:16:24,527
That being so, Ananda, remember this too as a wonderful and marvellous quality of the Buddha.

163
00:16:25,528 --> 00:16:33,418
Here, Ananda, for the Tathagata, feelings are known as they arise, as they are present, as they disappear.

164
00:16:34,178 --> 00:16:40,047
Perceptions are known as they arise, as they are present, and as they disappear.

165
00:16:40,346 --> 00:16:45,674
thoughts are known as they arise, as they are present, and as they disappear.

166
00:16:46,056 --> 00:16:53,287
Remember this too, Ananda, as a wonderful and marvellous quality of the Tathagata.

167
00:16:53,307 --> 00:16:56,412
So he brings us right back to what the Tathagata actually is.

168
00:16:56,893 --> 00:16:57,793
He's the one who knows.

169
00:16:58,274 --> 00:17:02,480
All this other stuff is, in a sense, immaterial.

170
00:17:02,500 --> 00:17:06,287
And then, Venerable Sir, since the Blessed One

171
00:17:06,570 --> 00:17:11,338
Blessed ones' feelings are known as they arise, as they are present, as they disappear.

172
00:17:11,960 --> 00:17:16,307
Perceptions are known as they arise, as they are present, as they disappear.

173
00:17:16,406 --> 00:17:20,453
Thoughts are known as they arise, as they are present, as they disappear.

174
00:17:20,534 --> 00:17:26,564
This too I remember as a wonderful and marvellous quality of the Blessed One.

175
00:17:26,584 --> 00:17:28,567
That is what the Venerable Ananda said.

176
00:17:28,606 --> 00:17:33,355
The teacher approved and the monks were satisfied, the listeners were satisfied.

177
00:17:33,587 --> 00:17:36,634
and delighted in Venerable Ananda's words.

178
00:17:39,779 --> 00:17:55,730
I can only hope that this has been a tremendous inspiration and that you will continue in your practice and attain that awareness of the Buddha sooner rather than later.

179
00:17:58,174 --> 00:18:03,662
And the listeners were highly delighted.

